<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920312-0080</DOCNO><DOCID>920312-0080.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Chevron Corp.:   Plan on Early Retirements   Offered to 35,000 Workers</HL><DATE>03/12/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4</SO><CO>   CHV LABOR</CO><MS>ENERGY (ENE)</MS><IN>OIL-INTEGRATED MAJORS (OIL)PETROLEUM (PET)</IN><NS>LABOR, PERSONNEL ISSUES (LAB)PETROLEUM MARKET (PET)</NS><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Chevron Corp., San Francisco, offered 35,000 of 40,000eligible employees an early retirement plan as part of itsefforts to trim its work force and become more competitive.   The plan is being offered to 35,000 Chevron employees onthe U.S. payroll with more than two years of service as ofMay 15. It supercedes an early retirement plan offered inJanuary to 3,000 employees whose age and years of servicetotaled 75. The company has a total world-wide work force of55,000.</LP><TEXT>   Chevron already took a $102 million charge in the fourthquarter for anticipated reductions of about 2,000 employees.That charge didn't include the work force at its Port Arthur,Texas, refinery, where the company plans to eliminate 700 ofthe current 1,900 jobs and shut one of its two crude oilprocessing units.   The revamped plan would, for example, offer an employeewith 15 years of service earning $45,500 a year a specialbenefit of $29,025 above the regular retirement plan payment.   A Chevron spokesman wouldn't say how many employees thecompany thought might accept the plan. He said the changedemonstrates that Chevron is &quot;quite serious about the need tocut costs.&quot;</TEXT></DOC>